'''Dame Sally Claire Davies''', [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]] (born 24 November 1949) is the [[Chief Medical Officer]] for England, and previously Director General of Research and Development and Chief Scientific Adviser for the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] and [[National Health Service]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nihr.ac.uk/events/Pages/BRC_Experimental_Medicine_Summer_School_2010.aspx|title=Dame Sally Davies becomes new Chief Medical Officer (interim)|publisher=[[National Institute for Health Research]]|accessdate=15 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=DofH>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Aboutus/MinistersandDepartmentLeaders/Departmentdirectors/Theseniorteam/DH_083897|title=Professor Dame Sally C. Davies|publisher=Department of Health (UK)|accessdate=15 December 2010}}</ref>

==Early life==
Davies was born to John and Emily (née Tordoff) Davies. She studied at [[Edgbaston High School for Girls]], Birmingham. She qualified as a medical doctor ([[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MB ChB]]) from the [[University of Manchester]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmc-uk.org/doctors/register/LRMP.asp|title=List of Registered Medical Practitioners (The online Register)|publisher=[[General Medical Council]]|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref>  She gained an [[Master of Science|MSc]] from the University of London.

==Career==
Davies was a member of the steering group for the Biotechnology Innovation and Growth Team, chaired by Sir [[David Cooksey]] and its “refresh” the Health Care Industry Task Force, and is a member of the UK Health Innovation Council. She specializes in the research of [[sickle cell disease]].<ref name=DofH/> She was a Consultant [[Hematology|Haematologist]] at the [[Central Middlesex Hospital]] (North West London NHS Trust) from 1985 until 2011. {{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}

===Chief Medical Officer===
From June 2010, Davies was the interim [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]] for HM Government although now has been confirmed as the permanent Chief Medical Officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conference.nhsconfed.org/speakers/Pages/SallyDavies.aspx|title=Professor Dame Sally Davies|publisher=NHS Confederation|accessdate=14 May 2011}}</ref>

==Awards and assessment==
In February 2013 she was assessed as the 6th most powerful woman in the United Kingdom by [[Woman's Hour]] on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007qlvb/features/power-list-100 BBC Radio 4, Woman's Hour Power list]</ref>

==Personal life==
She first married in 1974, divorcing in 1982. She remarried in 1982, but her second husband died that same year. She married her third husband in 1989, and they have two daughters. She has received honorary degrees from [[Keele University]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-14064082|accessdate=11 March 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=7 July 2011}}</ref> and the [[University of Lincoln]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorands|url=http://alumni.lincoln.ac.uk/page.aspx?pid=343|work=University of Lincoln}}</ref>

